Here's a step-by-step guide to creating a simple Discord bot using Node.js and the Discord.js library:
## Step 1: Install Node.js

First, ensure you have Node.js installed on your system. You can download it from the official Node.js website: https://nodejs.org/en/download/

## Step 2: Create a New Project Directory

Create a new folder for your bot project. For example, you can name it "discord-bot".

## Step 3: Initialize a New Node.js Project

Initiate a new Node.js project by running the following command in your bot folder:
```bash
npm init
```

This command will create a package.json file in your project directory. It will prompt you to fill in some information about your project, such as the project name, version, description, and author. You can fill in the details as per your preference.

## Step 4: Install Discord.js

Install the Discord.js library, which is a popular library for building Discord bots. Make sure to install version 14, which is the latest stable version at the time of writing:
```bash
npm install discord.js@14
```

## Step 5: Set Up a Discord Bot Application

Log in to the Discord developer portal at https://discord.com/developers/applications. Create a new bot application and give it a name and a description. Add a bot user to your application and copy the token that is generated for that bot user. You will need this token to run your bot.

## Step 6: Write the Bot Code

Create a file named index.js in your project directory. This will be the main file for your bot. Here's a basic structure for the code:
```js
const { Client, GatewayIntentBits } = require('discord.js');
const client = new Client({ intents: [GatewayIntentBits.presence, GatewayIntentBits.messageContent] });

client.on('ready', () => {
    console.log('Bot is ready!');
});

client.on('messageCreate', (message) => {
    if (message.content === 'ban me') {
        message.delete();
        message.channel.send('You have been banned for saying "ban me".');
    }
});

client.login('YOUR_BOT_TOKEN');
```

In this code:
- We require the Discord.js library and create a new Client object with the necessary intents for our bot to function.
- We set up event listeners for the "ready" event, which fires when the bot connects to Discord, and the "messageCreate" event, which fires when a new message is created in a channel.
- For the "messageCreate" event, we check if the message content is "ban me". If it is, we delete the message and send a response to the channel that the user has been banned.
- Finally, we use the login method with your bot token to authenticate and connect the bot to Discord.

## Step 7: Run the Bot

You can run the bot by using the following command:
```bash
node index.js
```

This will start your bot, and it should connect to Discord and be online. You can test your bot by sending the "ban me" command in a channel, and it should respond with a message indicating that the user has been banned.

Remember to replace "YOUR_BOT_TOKEN" with the actual token you obtained from the Discord developer portal.

